2.1 MiniLLM: Knowledge Distillation with Reverse KLD

In this work, we consider minimizing the reverse KLD between the student and teacher distributions as the learning objective of MINILLM:

Œ∏ = arg min J (Œ∏) = arg min KL[qŒ∏||p]

Œ∏

Œ∏

=

arg

min
Œ∏

E
x‚àºpx ,y ‚àºqŒ∏

log

qŒ∏(y|x) . p(y|x)

(1)

[Hus15] has shown that minimizing KL[qŒ∏||p] leads to a mode-seeking behavior, where qŒ∏ assigns high probabilities to p‚Äôs large modes, ignoring the small ones. Figure 2 illustrates the difference
between the two KLDs when a Gaussian distribution tries to fit a Gaussian mixture. We can see that minimizing forward KLD causes qŒ∏ to place large probability mass on the zero-probability places of p, which corresponds to the generation of low-quality texts in practice, while reverse KLD focuses on p‚Äôs major modes, which is crucial to ensure the correctness and faithfulness of language generation.

We term our KD method for LLMs by minimizing the reverse KLD as MINILLM, which is illustrated in Figure 3. Unlike sequence-level KD, MINILLM does not force qŒ∏ to fit all y sampled from the teacher distribution p. Instead, it encourages the student to generate samples preferred by the teacher
within its own capacities, which is more possible to achieve.

2.2 Optimization with Policy Gradient

Gradient Derivation We notice that the gradient of the objective function J (Œ∏) described in Equation (1) can be derived using the Policy Gradient Theorem [Wil92, HTAL17]:

